**Debouncing** delays execution until input stops for a set period. Each new keystroke resets the timer:

```javascript
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timer;
  return (...args) => {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => fn(...args), delay);
  };
}

const search = debounce((query) => {
  fetch(`/api/search?q=${query}`);
}, 300);

input.addEventListener('keyup', (e) => search(e.target.value));
```

Typing 'kubernetes' fires 0 requests until 300ms of silence, then fires 1. Related concept: **throttling** limits to at most one call per interval rather than waiting for a pause.

**WebSocket presence channels**. Unlike HTTP (request-response), a WebSocket holds a persistent, full-duplex TCP connection:

```
HTTP polling:  Client -> Server -> Client  (repeated)
WebSocket:     Client <=======> Server     (persistent)
```

```javascript
// Client subscribes to a presence channel
const ws = new WebSocket('wss://chat.example.com/room/42');

ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'typing', user: 'alice' }));

// Server broadcasts to all subscribers instantly
ws.onmessage = (event) => {
  const data = JSON.parse(event.data);
  if (data.type === 'typing') {
    showTypingIndicator(data.user);
  }
};
```

Presence channels also track who is online/offline by detecting connection drops. This is how Slack, Discord, and collaborative editors deliver real-time state.

**Health checks** -- the load balancer probes each backend on a regular interval:

```
LB ----> GET /healthz ----> Server A (200 OK)     [healthy]
LB ----> GET /healthz ----> Server B (200 OK)     [healthy]
LB ----> GET /healthz ----> Server C (timeout)    [unhealthy]
```

Typical configuration (NGINX example):
```nginx
upstream backend {
    server 10.0.1.1:8080;
    server 10.0.1.2:8080;
    server 10.0.1.3:8080;
}

server {
    location /healthz {
        access_log off;
        return 200 'ok';
    }
}
```

The LB removes failed servers from rotation after N consecutive failures (usually 2-3) and re-adds them once they pass checks again. This is why users stay unaware of backend failures.
